<div id="review_1573407062" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1573407062" />
    <a title="Carol Douglas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36792905-carol-douglas"><img alt="Carol Douglas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442460260p2/36792905.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1573407062?book_show_action=true">Mar 08, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol Douglas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol Douglas" href="/user/show/36792905-carol-douglas">Carol Douglas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400096985" href="/book/show/92936.Red_Azalea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1573407062" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer602639668447311774"> This is one woman&apos;s story of what it was like to be a girl sent to the countryside in China&apos;s Cultural Revolution. Anchee Min shows how hard it is to pick cotton all day, which of course reminded me of slavery in the United States. She also demonstrates how all-pervasive ideology was: Even endearments between sweethearts may be phrased in political slogans. <br/> The most unusual aspect of the book is the moving love relationship between two girls working in the same production team. Of course such </span>
  <span id="freeText602639668447311774" style="display:none"> This is one woman's story of what it was like to be a girl sent to the countryside in China's Cultural Revolution. Anchee Min shows how hard it is to pick cotton all day, which of course reminded me of slavery in the United States. She also demonstrates how all-pervasive ideology was: Even endearments between sweethearts may be phrased in political slogans. <br /> The most unusual aspect of the book is the moving love relationship between two girls working in the same production team. Of course such relationships were forbidden, and indeed all sexual relationships were.<br /> The story moves to Shanghai film studios, which were cutthroat. <br /> Towards the end, I liked the story less and found it less believable. But the fault may be in me. This is an autobiography, and I suppose I shouldn't doubt any of it. <br /> I am glad that Anchee Min was finally able to leave China, or her voice would have been silenced. She has gone on to write books about Jiang Qing, Mao's wife, and Mao himself. But of course they are present in this book, too, though not directly. They controlled China, and this book demonstrates that. </span>
  <a data-text-id="602639668447311774" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


