<div id="review_652681703" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/652681703" />
    <a title="Diane Yannick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1253673-diane-yannick"><img alt="Diane Yannick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468376907p2/1253673.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/652681703?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diane Yannick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diane Yannick" href="/user/show/1253673-diane-yannick">Diane Yannick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400096985" href="/book/show/92936.Red_Azalea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer652681703" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18395127806022484796">This is one of the most tedious books that I ever finished. It takes place in China during the Cultural Revolution. Achee Min left her home in a Shanghai tenement to join a labor collective where she lived by the rules of Mao&apos;s little red book. <br/><br/>Her oppressive life was described in excruciating detail. I sympathized with the methodical, authoritarian destruction of her spirit. However, I could not see the beauty of the storytelling which many have described as poetic. I did not gain many insights</span>
  <span id="freeText18395127806022484796" style="display:none">This is one of the most tedious books that I ever finished. It takes place in China during the Cultural Revolution. Achee Min left her home in a Shanghai tenement to join a labor collective where she lived by the rules of Mao's little red book. <br /><br />Her oppressive life was described in excruciating detail. I sympathized with the methodical, authoritarian destruction of her spirit. However, I could not see the beauty of the storytelling which many have described as poetic. I did not gain many insights into this time in China's history. I felt that much of the verbiage was self indulgent and downright boring. She described her lesbian relationship with an unconscionable amount of repetitive detail. Then later her partner has a heterosexual encounter in Min's house while Min acts as a lookout. Way too abrupt for me to fathom. There was another convoluted section about her becoming an actress for Madame Mao. As a reader, I was often left scratching my head. Inner dialog which would have given understanding was forsaken for monotonous detail. <br /><br />Here is an example of the writing that annoyed me: "We put on outfits that would make a good first impression. Firewood put on another vermilion shirt and sea-blue navy trousers. Cheering Spear dug out a garment printed with square patterns. Bee OhYang took out two slightly different colored white shirts and tried to make up her mind. I decided to wear my old uniform, the one given to me by Yan." A motionless cricket underneath one of the beds is described next. <br /><br />Min just published a new book. Guess who won't be reading it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18395127806022484796" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


