    <a title="Regina Lindsey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6693237-regina-lindsey"><img alt="Regina Lindsey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348604150p2/6693237.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/770870584?book_show_action=true">Nov 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Regina Lindsey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Regina Lindsey" href="/user/show/6693237-regina-lindsey">Regina Lindsey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781400096985" href="/book/show/92936.Red_Azalea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer770870584" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11864929330288703089">Anchee Min, best known for her historical fiction work set in China grew up during the Cultural Revolution under Mao. Early on she showed great promise as a daughter of the Revolution even considering, at one time, turning her parents for counter-revolutionary thoughts and actions. However, when she was forced to lead a public denouncement of her teacher Min began to awaken to the reality of China and Communism.<br/>In many ways this book was incredibly disappointing. While I admit I&apos;ve never read Mi</span>
  <span id="freeText11864929330288703089" style="display:none">Anchee Min, best known for her historical fiction work set in China grew up during the Cultural Revolution under Mao. Early on she showed great promise as a daughter of the Revolution even considering, at one time, turning her parents for counter-revolutionary thoughts and actions. However, when she was forced to lead a public denouncement of her teacher Min began to awaken to the reality of China and Communism.<br />In many ways this book was incredibly disappointing. While I admit I've never read Min's fictional work, I expected more from her writing. Instead the the writing is surprisingly spare. The book is at its best the first half of the book as Min begins to shed some of her naivety towards the Revolution and daily life under this regime. I found her father the most tragic figure. Min really brings home how difficult it is for an individual to have his/her dream stripped from them for no other purpose other than the government deems it so. But, I was barely interested in the story after Min leaves the communal farm.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11864929330288703089" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


